                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d831">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3331/148: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-03-18T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 18, 1938—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. Your despatch No. 39, March 4, 1938.<note n="22" xml:id="d831fn22">Not
                        printed.</note> Since it is not the practice of the Department to seek
                    exclusive preferential facilities of any nature for American trade, it does not
                    believe that you should take any action along the line indicated in your
                    despatch under reference. There is also a strong possibility that the particular
                    type of action you suggest would be held by the Treasury Department to be a
                    bounty or grant within the meaning of Section 303 of the Tariff Act of
                        1930,<note n="23" xml:id="d831fn23">46 Stat. 590, 687.</note> and to
                    necessitate the imposition of equivalent countervailing duties, such as were
                    imposed upon German products as a result of roughly comparable practices.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
